## Development rules

### Workflow-specific (CcC)
1. **Phase discipline.** Use `/spec` for new features or architectural changes before writing code; use `/research` when touching unfamiliar tech; use `/notes` at the end of each session; use `/continue` to recover context after compaction.
2. **Pre-flight every commit.** Before `git commit`, ask yourself: "Will Codex block this?" Stage a clean worktree, split oversized diffs (default cap: 5000 lines), ensure the diff addresses a single concern. The pre-commit hook will auto-run Codex; treat its VERDICT as authoritative.
3. **Read REVIEW.md before finalizing a commit.** If Codex applied non-trivial fixes or left a `WARN`, summarize that context in the commit body so history stays auditable.
4. **Re-read this file after every context compaction** (pre-compaction hook injects a reminder — follow it).
5. **Maintain IMPLEMENTATION_NOTES.md.** One entry per session: status, what was done, decisions, open questions, next steps.

### Code quality
6. Keep code simple — no dead code, no speculative abstractions
7. Do NOT add features beyond what the spec / user request covers
8. Comment only where the logic is non-obvious; well-named identifiers beat comments
9. Read the source-of-truth files before modifying anything
10. Never commit unrelated/unstaged files

### Interaction & safety
11. Do not stop to ask for confirmation on routine decisions — the user is not at the keyboard for every step
12. Ask before destructive operations (rm -rf, force push, schema drops, external messages)
13. Internet access is restricted to the `/research` skill. Outside that skill, do not run WebSearch/WebFetch or install new remote dependencies without explicit user permission.
14. No new dependencies without explicit approval

### Deliverables
15. All project artifacts in English (AGENTS.md, SPEC.md, code comments, commit messages). Converse with the user in the configured conversation language.
16. Keep this file aligned with the actual workflow and tests. Update README.md if CLI/runtime behavior changes.
17. Run `[test command]` before declaring a task done.

